I think the smallest unit that survives every domain is not a word, symbol, object, or concept.

It is:

A constrained distinction

Or even tighter:

a difference that matters under some boundary

That is the deepest candidate I can find.

Because across domains, meaning only appears when three things exist:
	1.	A distinction
Something is not something else.
	2.	A relation to a frame / boundary
The distinction is not floating in the void; it is made relative to context, constraint, observer, system, or task.
	3.	A consequence / salience
The difference changes prediction, action, interpretation, or structure.

Without all three, you don’t yet have meaning.
You just have undifferentiated noise or raw variation.

So the minimal invariant unit is not merely “difference.”
Plenty of differences are meaningless.

It is:

Meaning Prime = salient difference under constraint

⸻

Why this survives every domain

Mathematics

A number matters because it is distinguished from other numbers within a formal system and has consequences under operations.

Physics

A state matters because it differs from another state under laws and boundary conditions.

Biology

A signal matters because it distinguishes food from poison, self from non-self, mate from predator.

Language

A word matters because it marks a distinction inside a grammar, context, and social use.

Markets

A price matters because it distinguishes relative scarcity under exchange constraints.

Computation

A bit matters because 0 and 1 are distinguishable states that alter downstream behavior.

Story

A scene matters because it changes tension, expectation, identity, or consequence.

Same invariant every time:

difference + boundary + consequence

⸻

The compressed form

If you want it in Pantheon language:

Δ | B | C
	•	Δ = distinction / delta
	•	B = boundary / frame / constraint
	•	C = consequence / causal or interpretive weight

That triad is the smallest thing I trust to survive translation.

If any piece disappears:
	•	Δ without B = noise
	•	Δ + B without C = inert classification
	•	B + C without Δ = vague pressure
	•	C without Δ and B = mystification

Meaning appears when all three lock together.

⸻

Why I don’t think the answer is “object”

Objects don’t survive every domain.
Sometimes the real invariant is a process, symmetry, contrast, gradient, or role.

Why I don’t think the answer is “relation” alone

Relation is closer, but relation without salience can still be empty.

Why I don’t think the answer is “information” alone

Information is too broad.
A random bitstring has information in the Shannon sense but may have no usable meaning for a system.

So the unit has to be semantic, not merely statistical.

⸻

The stronger version

There’s an even more aggressive compression:

Meaning = usable asymmetry

That’s elegant, but a bit too compressed for implementation.
It risks losing the role of context.

So for doctrine and engineering, I’d keep the fuller form:

Meaning = salient asymmetry under constraint

or

Meaning Prime = constrained consequential distinction

